Leading Edge
Preview
A metabolic balance of GLP-1
and NMDA receptors in the brain
Jessica T.Y. Yue,1 Ameth N. Garrido,2,3 and Tony K.T. Lam2,3,4,5,*
1Department of Physiology, Alberta Diabetes Institute, Neuroscience and Mental Health Institute, and Group on Molecular and Cell Biology of
Lipids, University of Alberta, Edmonton, AB, Canada
2Toronto General Hospital Research Institute, UHN, Toronto, ON, Canada
3Department of Physiology, University of Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
4Department of Medicine, University of Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
5Banting and Best Diabetes Centre, University of Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
*Correspondence: tonykt.lam@uhn.ca
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2024.06.031
Glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) and N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors in the brain regulate metabolic
homeostasis. In a paper published in Nature, Petersen et al. describe a bimodal molecule that conjugates a
GLP-1 analog with MK-801 (NMDA receptor antagonist), which lowers feeding and body weight to a greater
extent than the GLP-1R agonist alone.
Obesity is a metabolic disorder, clinically
deﬁned as a body mass index of greater
than or equal to 30 kg/m2, that affects an
estimated 422 million people globally ac-
cording to the World Health Organization.1
Social determinants of health are impor-
tant factors contributing to its regional
global prevalence.1 Obesity predisposes
patients to type 2 diabetes, metabolic-
dysfunction-associated steatotic liver dis-
ease (MASLD), cardiometabolic disorders,
and several cancers, and so the quest for
more efﬁcacious anti-obesity therapies ra-
ges on. The introduction of incretin-based
medicines such as GLP-1 receptor (GLP-
1R) agonists for weight-loss therapy has
provided alternative therapeutic modalities
for patients, although patients exhibit less
weight loss as compared to bariatric sur-
gery.2 The development of co-/tri-agonists
coupling the actions of GLP-1 with other
incretins and/or hormones like glucagon
has resulted in enhanced weight loss
compared to GLP-1R agonists and is
beginning to bridge the gap between
weight loss achieved with medication and
weight loss from bariatric surgery.3 To pro-
vide effective options for less invasive
treatments for obesity, it is therefore
essential that novel GLP-1R-based drugs
be investigated. A recent Nature paper by
Petersen et al.4 describes a new incretin-
based
compound
that
induces
pro-
nounced weight loss when injected subcu-
taneously into rodent models of metabolic
disease.
Petersen and colleagues describe a
bimodal molecule capable of directing
N-methyl-D-aspartate receptor (NMDAR)
antagonism to cells expressing GLP-1R
to potently lower body weight and reduce
food intake to a greater extent than GLP-
1R agonist alone while maintaining energy
expenditure in diet-induced obese (DIO)
mice over 10–14 days. By conjugating
MK801, an NMDAR antagonist, to an
analog of GLP-1 through a cleavable linker,
the authors
demonstrate that GLP-1-
MK801-induced weight loss is achieved
whilelesseningthe undesirablesideeffects
of NMDAR antagonism such as hyperloco-
motion, which had previously precluded
compounds like MK801 from clinical use,
by limiting the actions of NMDAR blockade
to GLP-1R-expressing regions. Similarly,
taste aversion tests reveal somewhat
milder aversion in GLP-1-MK801-treated
mice than in semaglutide-treated mice,
suggesting that inhibition of NMDAR may
help mitigate some adverse effects of
GLP-1R agonist treatment.
GLP-1-MK801 subcutaneously injected
for 5 days altered gene expression and
proteins in the hypothalamus of DIO
mice, including upregulation of genes
related to neuron-to-neuron communica-
tion (synaptic function and glutamatergic
signaling). This suggests that changes to
the neural plasticity in the hypothalamus
may be one way by which GLP-1-MK801
exerts its anoretic effects to reduce body
weight differently from GLP-1. Of note,
GLP-1-MK801 also yielded some overlap-
ping transcriptional and proteomic signa-
tures with GLP-1 and MK801, indicating
that the compound retains some common
signaling pathways to its parent deriva-
tives. GLP-1-MK801 treatment for 9 days
in DIO melanocortin-4 receptor (Mc4r)-
knockout mice induced weight loss to a
similar extent as wild-type mice of the
same treatment duration, indicating that
GLP-1-MK801 works independently of
the melanocortin pathway as well.
GLP-1 analogs like Ozempic (semaglu-
tide)
are
potent
anti-hyperglycemic
agents, while GLP-1 co-agonist therapies
are currently being evaluated for their roles
in improving lipid metabolism, particularly
in
MASLD.5
Petersen
and
colleagues
report that in DIO mice, 14 days of GLP-
1-MK801 treatment lowered plasma tri-
glycerides to a similar extent as GLP-1
treatment compared to vehicle and MK-
801 controls and lowered plasma choles-
terol better than GLP-1 alone. In rats fed
with an obesogenic diet, 5 days of GLP-
1-MK801 lowered plasma triglycerides
but had no effect on plasma cholesterol
levels. Furthermore, the conjugate did not
affect markers of liver damage, but it re-
mains to be seen whether GLP-1-MK801
can improve liver lipid metabolism. In dia-
betic db/db mice, GLP-1-MK801 treat-
ment lowered hyperglycemia to the same
extent as semaglutide, although both
showed greater reductions in glycemia
during acute versus chronic treatment. In
