DIO mice, GLP-1-MK801 and GLP-1 treat-
ments had similar acute glucose-lowering
effects and improvements in glucose toler-
ance; thus, NMDAR antagonism in GLP-
1R-expressing cells does not appear to
confer added glycemic improvements to
GLP-1R activation alone, although modest
improvements to insulin sensitivity as
measured with an insulin tolerance test
were seen. Overall, this timely and elegant
study conducted by Petersen et al. has
discovered
additional
weight-lowering
beneﬁts of a joint activation of GLP-1R
and inhibition of NMDAR over GLP-1R
activation per se and greatly strengthens
research efforts that aim to design com-
pounds that are conjugated with GLP-1
agonism3 to exert superior metabolic regu-
lation in obesity and diabetes.
Although the study by Petersen et al.
paves the way for the potential to begin
testing the clinical relevance of GLP-1-
MK801 treatment in people with obesity,
some
unknowns
in
rodents
warrant
urgent investigation. For example, what
are the metabolic (i.e., weight-, lipid-,
and glucose-lowering) effects of GLP-1-
MK801 in the hypothalamus vs. other brain
regions, such as the recently well-studied
dorsal vagal complex? The fact that GLP-
1-MK801 is administered subcutaneously4
impliesthatGLP-1-MK801 shouldhavenot
only elucidated molecular changes in the
hypothalamus as described4 but also at
the very least in the dorsal vagal complex
(Figure 1). In fact, direct administration of
MK801 into the dorsal vagal complex, un-
like the hypothalamus, instead increases
food intake,6 while direct activation of
NMDAR in the dorsal vagal complex is
sufﬁcient to lower feeding, weight, hepatic
glucose production, and triglyceride-en-
riched very-low-density lipoprotein secre-
tion.7,8 Thus, in light of the opposing
metabolic effects of NMDAR in the hypo-
thalamus vs. dorsal vagal complex, would
direct GLP-1-MK801 infusion into the hy-
pothalamus vs. dorsal vagal complex exert
similar or differential effects? What are
the cell-speciﬁc mechanisms within the
hypothalamus (i.e., Arc, VMN, PVN, and
SCN) and dorsal vagal complex (i.e.,
NTS and AP) that are mediating the
effect
of
GLP-1-MK801
(Figure
1)?
Given that the non-classical NMDA recep-
tors containing NR1/NR3 subunits are
resistant to MK801,9 are the classical
NR1/NR2-containing NMDARs targeted
Figure 1. A balanced metabolic attack of GLP-1 and NMDA receptors in the brain
A subcutaneous administration of GLP-1-directed NMDA receptor antagonist MK801 (GLP-1-MK801)
potentially targets the hypothalamus of rodents to lower food intake and weight. Published studies have
documented that MK801 administration into the dorsal vagal complex of rodents increases food intake,
while administration into the hypothalamus decreases food intake. Future studies are warranted to assess
the metabolic effects of GLP-1-MK801 in the hypothalamus and dorsal vagal complex, as both regions are
targeted by a rise of GLP-1-MK801 in the blood circulation, and such investigation carries the potential to
elucidate balanced metabolic beneﬁts of targeting GLP-1R and NMDAR in the brain. PVN, paraventricular
nucleus; VMN, ventromedial nucleus; Arc, arcuate nucleus; SCN, suprachiasmatic nucleus; DVC, dorsal
vagal complex; AP, area postrema; NTS, nucleus tractus solitarius; DMX, dorsal motor vagal nucleus.
